{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492607"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:37:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:37:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1109"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1109"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.07,0,0.64,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43510"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1109"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28511"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"347"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44498"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43510"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless swelling in her neck that has been present for three weeks. She has no other symptoms, no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, the lump is clearly visible (Image), non-tender and smooth-surfaced. Ultrasonography demonstrated a cystic lesion. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Caseating necrosis","Branchial cyst","Epidermoid cyst"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe neck lump described and displayed in the image can be best identified by its location in the neck. It is sitting about two-thirds of the way up the anterior aspect of the sternocleidomastoid muscle. This is the typical site of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranchial cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. These congenital abnormalities typically appear in the second or third decades of life and occasionally, as in this patient, can appear later. They are often asymptomatic but can become enlarged and tender if they become infected and frequently change in size during an upper respiratory tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroglossal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are one of the most common causes of midline neck lumps. They are located more anterior-medially on the neck below the hyoid bone and are developed from remnants of the thyroid gland. They most commonly present during childhood between 2-10 years age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystic hygromas\u003C/strong\u003E are congenital malformations of the lymphatic ducts. They are also common in paediatric populations and are very rare to present in adulthood. They are commonly found in the posterior triangle of the neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is derived from the upper portion of a hair follicle and are filled with keratin. They are typically 1-3cm in size (much smaller than the lump in the image) and can often be diagnosed clinically based on their appearance - firm, round, yellowish, fixed nodule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaseating necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is frequently seen in tuberculosis infections and other infectious diseases. It describes a form of cell death where the tissue forms a cheese-like appearance. It can infect the hilar lymph nodes, but would be rare to have the appearance shown in the image or this distribution of lymph nodes in the neck and the woman is asymptomatic in terms of an infectious point of view, hence is an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thyroglossal cysts are the most common cause of midline neck masses in children.","A common way to establish the cause of a neck lump is its location.","Cystic hygromas are seen more commonly in paediatric populations.","Branchial cysts are commonly located in the upper third of the anterior aspect of the sternocleidomastoid muscle."],"references":["Knipe, H. Thyroglossal duct cyst. In: Radiopaedia [online]. 2020 Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/thyroglossal-duct-cyst","Auerbach N, Gupta G, Mahajan K. Cystic Hygroma. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560672/","Lam M, DeGroote M. Epidermoid cyst. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2020. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/epidermoid-cyst/.","Panchbhai AS, Choudhary MS. Branchial cleft cyst at an unusual location: a rare case with a brief review. Dentomaxillofac Radiol. 2012;41(8):696-702. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22116133/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28511"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1109"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15314"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15314"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e96306b3-b88a-4fb7-ae46-12ba651018ee.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e96306b3-b88a-4fb7-ae46-12ba651018ee.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28511","links":